Location: UMUSAMBI VILLAGE - Wetlands and Grey Crowned Crane rehabilitation

Observation Details: A group of four are heard almost daily on the campus, and I have seen them in the past although not seen but only heard on 8 May. They are large, noisy bulbuls. They are mostly uniform brown with a yellow throat. Although they resemble the Simple Greenbuls which also occur in the area, they are easily distinguished by the yellow throat and the lack of white marks around the eyes. This flock generally is seen or heard in the trees and shrubs along the Yah River (which runs through the campus) and the adjacent marsh. One of these birds was photographed on 21 December 2019 (photo added).

Observation Details: One of those moments where I wished for a good camera. Watched the warbler fly down to the ground twenty feet in front of me and grab a small fish that appeared to have been left when the water level of the river went down. Definitely the first time I've watched a warbler eat a fish! The warbler proceeded to bash the fish around for a minute or two, and then swallowed it. Having eaten, it flew a few feet over to the water's edge and took a bath.
